content.description:
The route is located on the Wall of Marching Munchkins. Some new routes have appeared on this wall, so don't rely on counting the bolted lines in Squeezing II alone. 

  Start up on a good sidepull to very thin face and moves off of small to non-existent (smear) footholds. The crux is located at bolts 3 and 4. The climbing gets easier up high and then has some interesting slab moves to get to the anchors.
content.protection: Bolts (7); well protected. Chains for rappel/lower.
content.location: The climb is just to the right of We're Not In Kansas Anymore (11c). It is also located to the left of a short new route ~40 ft. long route put up by EFR, et al. The rating on this climb is said to be 11+ but after working the first few moves, I can tell you it may be significantly more difficult......

content.description:
Short hard crux of thin face moves down low with more moderate climbing to the anchors. There are some fun reaches getting to the shelf and then a bit more sustain pump above that. 

  Maybe one can aid to the 2nd bolt and then redpoint from there and call it 11a or so...
content.location: left of "we're not in kansas anymore"

content.description: Hard moves into and off of an undercling.  The move is not intuitive and has thwarted many an onsight specialist.  As with most routes at this crag the crux is down low but it is well protected.  This route is hard to impossible if you are below 5'6".  We have painted a yellow line at the bottom, if you can't touch it ignore this rating.  (Just kidding)!
content.location: Just right of Ruby Slippers.  The first moves lead to a pronounced undercling.

content.description:
Lots of very important footwork on this route. You gotta have your sequence nailed. Its a tricky one to figure out. 

xxx Beware xxx Onsight Spoiling Beta:

  Start on large foothold ledges with extremely thin hands. I mean THIN crimps, but the feet are so good that it is not too bad. Dance your way up a few moves to some sidepulls so that you are like a human pair of locking pliers. Crank hard with technical foot work to gain the 2nd clip. Then a tricky move right yields to you the hold that you want. Work your way up this sidepull system to a nice slot on the left by the 3rd bolt and get ready to sustain pump non-obvious moves to the 4th bolt. Then you are golden with 5.9/10 moves to the top.
content.location: Between the 2 12a's on the main munchkin wall. 6th route from the left after the 2 easy(5.4, 5.5) routes in the Towers area. It starts on the large, (3 inch deep, 10 inch long) foothold about 2 ft off the ground.

content.description: I have not seen any description of this either here on MP or in Squeezing The Lemmon II, although since Munchkinland is such a popular area I am sure others must have done it before...regardless here it is:   Between "Lions And Tigers And Bears!" and "There's No Place Like Home" is a right arching thin finger crack. Follow the crack up to the roof, step a foot or two left on the ledge below the roof then turn the roof and follow the intermittent cracks up to the anchors of "There's No Place Like Home".
content.protection: Nuts and small to medium cams with chain anchors. Offset brass nuts were also helpful.
content.location: Follow the right arching crack between "Lions And Tigers And Bears!" and "There's No Place Like Home", the 2ed and 3rd bolted routes on the Wall Of The Marching Munchkins respectively.

content.description:
Starts up the obvious crack behind a tree right of ...And Toto Too. Pretty fun. Decent gear. You have to use the anchors to the left or right. Best part about this climb is you can lean back on the tree to place gear or send a text message. If you were planning on going to the Wall of the Trundling Trolls, but now you're feeling lazy, you can use your gear here.

 One day we were heading to Wall of the Trundling Trolls but hung out at Munchkinland too long, and it was my daughter's nap time. Someone said here's a gear route. I climbed it. I don't know anything else about it. I also suck at grading climbs and give too many stars to everything that goes generally up.
content.location: Obvious crack behind little tree.

climbs.name: Tree Wing Circus
climbs.fa: Wing Ng, JSt, EFR, Robert McLeod, '06

content.description: A bit close to a tree at times. Some choose to use the tree rather than hanging on a bolt. You might have to take off a number grade or two if you do this, but it is still climbing.  If you don't think about it being there you will hardly notice it and probably will not use the tree.  Rumor has that The Viking did.
content.location: On the right end of the Wall of Marching Munchkins just right of Because Because Because.  Starts from the top of the taller of two tombstone like rocks at the base of the cliff.

content.description: Fairly sustained climbing, fun.  Crux is not only getting over the roof, but to the next bolt.  Backwards from many Munchkinland climbs in having a relatively easy start to thinner moves above.
content.location: Third route from left on main Wall of Marching Munchkins.

content.description: Difficult start left of first bolt, then make your way right. Fairly sustained 5.10 climbing. Definitely worth doing.
content.location: 4th route from left on main munchkin wall

content.description: Like most Munchkinland routes the crux is low.  The tree is close but not in the way and not very helpful.
content.location: Starts just to the right of The Wiz.

content.description: The crux is near the bottom.  It is a great sequence with interesting feet. Pass through to easier climbing above.  If the route was a little more sustained at the grade, it would probably get three stars.  Depending on your sequence, the crux will feel pretty hard or not so bad.
content.location: The route just left of the u-shaped tree.  There is a distinctive curved seam near the bottom.

content.description: Tricky start with crux about midway.
content.location: 9th route from left end of the Wall of Marching Munchkins.  It is just right of the tree to the next to "Steel Man Tin Edges" (which has distinctive brown bolt hangers).  Shares the first bolt with "How Do You Like Them Apples".  "Poppies" goes left, "Apples" goes right.

content.description: Nice moderate route with good pro and a couple of bolts that protect this and the route to the left.
content.location: Far right end of the Wall of the Marching Munchkins.  Crack system just right of orange bolted face and big pine.

content.description: Fun route, reasonably sustained, good variety of moves and holds, a little spiciness but well protected.  The usual Munchkinland stuff, but better than average quality.  Pay attention up high so you don't go the wrong way.(Watch for prints left by the Chalk Monster).
content.location: First route right of the curved tree.  Directly in front of the tree is "Who's Your Wizard" which has brown hangars.  "Munchkinland" is just to the right.

content.description: Hard start and sustained climbing. There is a crux on the top half just before the last bolt.
content.location: 2nd to last route on main wall. Starts on black stained rock left of tree.

content.description:
I don't want to tell you where the crux is.  Just know that it's the hardest part of the climb. After the crux, it's 9ish climbing to the chains.   

  Guidebook = 11a. I thought more like solid 11, even though there's only a couple hard moves.
content.location: 2nd route from left on the Wall of The Marching Munchkins.

content.description: Face climbing to slabby section then over the bulge.
content.location: First (leftmost) route on the main wall, just right of the 5.4 and 5.5.

climbs.name: If I Only Had a Brain

content.description: A little more technical than burly, but sustained enough to make you work.  Good route.
content.location: Just right of the middle of the main wall, left of Ruby Slippers which is in front of the obvious curved tree.

climbs.name: How Do You Like Them Apples

content.description: Thin start to crimpy sidepulling.  Hope you've got titanium fingertips.
content.location: Tenth route from the left end of the Wall of Marching Munchkins.  Shares the first bolt with Poppies Will Make Them Sleep, then heads right.

content.description: Insanely hard, sharp start with lousy feet into some longer reaches and lots of sharp side-pulling.  Sustained.   The book calls this 11-.  My partner and I felt it was a full number grade harder than Ruby Slippers.
content.location: Left of "If Only I Had A Brain"

content.description: Typical Munchkin 5.10, fairly sustained, variety of holds, etc.
content.location: Second bolted line from the right end of the Wall of Marching Munchkins (main wall).  Rightmost route is "Tree Wing Circus" and has brown hangars.  "Because..." starts just a couple feet left.

content.description: Crux down low and sketchy around second bolt, but good moves.
content.protection: Bolts.  Anchors are big shuts with gates.  Makes cleaning the anchors easy.
content.location: Third route from right end of Wall of Marching Munchkins.  Second line right of obvious curved tree.

content.description: Munchkin Wall is a long cliffband of pretty good rock that faces in a generally northern direction along the ridgetop. There's a pretty good range of difficulty here, from 5.7 all the way to 5.12. This is a pretty good spot for the hotter parts of the year, but get an early start as the sun swings around and will hit the face later in the day from the west. Very popular climbing area!
